metadata.name: GM.GEN.MATH #50
metadata.description:
Released on the occasion of the Tribute to Herbert W. Franke.
100% of the proceeds from primary sales are donated to the Foundation Herbert W. Franke. 
https://www.tribute-hwf.com/

~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

Undisputably, my mathematical background makes me naturally attracted to graphs, math functions, and transformations. I use math in ways that mathematicians could consider nonsense, but which produce fascinating aesthetic elements for creation (to paraphrase Herbert W. Franke). Combining scientific symbols and illustrations with fictional data produces pseudo-persuasive generative imagery that we can easily take to be absolute truth or in which we find meaningful patterns.
In the special issue of Leonardo, Visual Mathematics from 1992, Herbert W. Franke and Horst S. Helbig published the article Generative Mathematics: Mathematically Described and Calculated Visual Art.

They propose that â€œThrough the use of [mathematical] formulas (software) we gain generative principles. Beyond formal descriptions, we obtain guides for the construction of images. For example, if we use a parametric representation of a curve, the result is similar to traditional methods of drawing and painting [â€¦]â€œ Additionally, mathematics removes frame limits and adds the possibilities for transitions, transformations, movement, and interaction by implementing simple changes to the defining parameters.

Iâ€™m also very fond of the analysis and comparison (mentioned there) of digitally generated images and Constructivist design. Limitations of the technology (in the 70s) allowed only simple line drawings, based on fixed proportions same as Constructivists did. â€œIn a short time, all possible features were exhausted, so it became an obvious goal to try to extend them. This was done first by the use of random generators â€” a highly interesting expansion of design principles [â€¦]â€ Another expansion happened by adding curved shapes, first simple then complex that overcame possibilities of drawing with compasses and rulers. â€œ[â€¦] oscillating curves are easily obtained through mathematical formulas and computer-graphic systems. The results we achieve on this basis do not look like Constructivist presentations, but their rationality and precision derive from Constructivist principles. â€

~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

Each mint contains both dark and light version, use D/N keys to switch between â€œday & nightâ€.
 
Base shapes are circles or Lissajous curves modified by the noise function. Shapes are arranged in a grid or by a circle packing algorithm. Lines are drawn smoothly or in stripes. Around 20% of the mints have lines in only one color (black/white). 

Depending on the browser/configuration rendering times will vary.

metadata.name: Bento Boxes #255
metadata.description:
Everybody needs a bento box in the cryptowinter.
The project calls for an adopted nostalgia of little kids that has been handed bento box by their parents before schoolâ€” a little moment of protected comfort before heading out for an adventure.

â€¢ â€¢ â€¢

The first collaboration project of MEK.txt and IceRain in FXHash. A work based on MEK.txtâ€™s â€œThe Bento Boxesâ€ and IceRainâ€™s excellent codes, Bento Boxes aims to be a fun visual and code exploration project on the generative art corridor. Pure code, no libraries.

Bento Boxes deconstructed the visual system on MEK.txt's artwork, titled almost similarly, â€œThe Bento Boxesâ€. Rebuilt it from scratch with codes, adding variants of colours and shapesâ€” without losing the strong characteristics of the base artwork.

Features:
- Striped Background
- Shadows
- Vapors
- Horizontal Vapors
- Meteors
- Colored Meteors
- White Moon (0.5%)

SVG being a vectorial format, this work can be displayed/printed at any size.
Press 's' on Live View to save the SVG.
Press 'p' on Live View using a Chromium based browser to export as PNG.

Also, to fully enjoy your piece, I'd suggest to use a Chromium based browser as the SVG renderer gives more details.

metadata.name: fx(haish) / the Generator #219
metadata.description:
fx(haish) is my contribution to #fxhashturnsone
fx(haish) is not a finished product
fx(haish) is a co-creation experiment
fx(haish) is a fun exploration of a mixed GenAI process

fx(haish) is my Happy Birthday to fx(hash). 

Have fun, collectors!


// HOW TO PARTICIPATE

Step 1. Mint or collect â€œfx(haish) - the Generatorâ€
Step 2. Visit https://www.arqtistic.com/fx(haish) to generate your â€œfx(haish) - The AI Cityâ€ based on your mint. You have 20 tries.
Step 3. Await further instructions.


// FURTHER INFO

This algorithm has been designed to produce images which are suitable for the subsequent AI generation. The token consists of a random number of randomly placed and sized rectangles, filled with a noise gradient pattern. In short, Diffusion AI Models thrive on noise.

The AI generation uses Stable Diffusion 1.5 through an API designed by the 330ai team (@Pixelmindai). The WebUI has been developed by Nik0gda (@AntonCebanu2). AI Prompt has been designed (by me) to produce images of Cities, but you can possibly make it do other things, if you try hard enough.

metadata.name: Blobby #55
metadata.description:
A sphere that has been contorted (or not) in various fashions! 

The spike level indicates how dense the protrusions are and the displacement level indicates how far these protrusions go. If any of those are 0, you'll get a flat sphere.
